er, interest in restoring ancient dyes increased among European scholars. In the Jewish case, rabbis and scientists attempted to reproduce the ancient tekhelet dye. The resulting dyes were gradually accepted in the ritual life of many Orthodox Jews. In addition to being a dye playing a role in Jewish ritual, blue features prominently in the Jewish mystical tradition, in Jewish magic and popular custom, and in Jewish eschatology. Blue is also representative of the Zionist movement, and it is the only chromatic color in the national flag of the State of Israel.Through the study of the changing roles and meanings attributed to the color blue in Judaism, Jewish Blues sheds new light on the power of a visual symbol in shaping the imagination of Jews throughout history. The use of the color blue continues to reflect pressing issues for Jews in our present era, as it has become a symbol of Jewish modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCabalaxColor. 0aColor. 0aColorsxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aSymbolism of colors. 4aHistory of Jewish People and Culture. 4aInterdisciplinary-Jewish Studies. 4aReligion-Judaism. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aIsaac Herzog.  aJewish Enlightenment.  aJewish history.  aState of Israel.  abible.  aclothing.  aculture.  adye.  ahasidism hasidic.  akabbalah.  amagic.  amedieval.  amessianism messianic.  amodern.  amysticism.  aorthodox.  arabbinic.  asymbolism.  atabernacle.  atassels.  atekhelet.  atemple.  atheocracy.  atsitsit.  azionism zionist.40uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9781512823387?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512823387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512823387/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PP